{
  "id": "a20050a4-919c-4182-90fe-5ab1c3ef10ca",
  "slug": "california-discovery-separate-statement-generator",
  "name": "Separate Statement of Discovery Responses (CA)",
  "summary": "This skill guides drafting a California-compliant Separate Statement for discovery motions under California Rules of Court, rule 3.1345, presenting each request, response, and the factual and legal basis for compelling further responses in a court-usable, request-by-request format. It emphasizes verbatim accuracy, device-specific deficiency analysis, meet-and-confer integration, tailored orderable remedies, and alignment with the broader motion package. The skill embeds anti-hallucination guardrails for all statutory and case citations and requires attorney verification for deadlines, legal authorities, and any sealing or privacy issues before filing.",
  "content": "# Separate Statement of Discovery Responses (California)\n\n## 1. Opening Context\n\nThis skill produces a California-compliant Separate Statement to support a motion involving discovery requests\u2014most commonly a motion to compel further responses\u2014where California Rules of Court, rule 3.1345, requires the moving party to present each discovery request, the responding party's response, and the moving party's reasons for compelling further responses in a structured, request-by-request format. In practice, the Separate Statement is not a mere exhibit; it is often the document the judge or research attorney reads most closely to evaluate the dispute. Under rule 3.1345(c), the statement must be \"full and complete so that no person is required to review any other document in order to determine the full request and the full response.\" That directive is practical: the court wants to see the exact words, not paraphrases.\n\nPoor execution is costly. A Separate Statement that is incomplete, disorganized, or mismatched to the motion can trigger denial without reaching the merits, invite sanctions exposure under Code of Civil Procedure section 2023.010, or undermine credibility by overstating what was asked or what was answered. Good execution looks like disciplined, record-anchored advocacy: each request is reproduced verbatim, the response is quoted exactly (including objections and any \"subject to\" language), and the deficiency explanation ties directly to the governing standard for the particular discovery device and the relief requested\u2014all while anticipating the responding party's likely defenses.\n\n## 2. Understanding the Context and Purpose\n\nIn California civil practice, discovery motions are heavily procedural and document-driven. Courts expect the moving party to narrow issues, present the disputed material accurately, and demonstrate why further responses or other relief are required under the Civil Discovery Act. The Separate Statement serves three strategic functions.\n\nFirst, it functions as a decision tool for the court. Rather than forcing the judge to flip between propounded requests, responses, meet-and-confer letters, and declarations, the Separate Statement consolidates the dispute into an item-by-item presentation. A motion to compel may involve dozens of distinct interrogatories, document demands, or requests for admission; the Separate Statement centralizes everything the court needs to rule on each item.\n\nSecond, it forces advocacy discipline. Because the document is organized request-by-request, it is difficult to hide overbreadth, poor drafting, or lack of linkage between the request and the asserted need. If the original request is sloppy, the Separate Statement will expose it. Conversely, if the responding party's objections are boilerplate or evasive, the Separate Statement is where you demonstrate that deficiency concretely by placing the request, the objection, and your reasoning in immediate proximity.\n\nThird, it is part of the motion's credibility package. Discovery judges are attuned to exaggeration and omission. If you quote responses selectively or bury meet-and-confer concessions, opposing counsel will highlight those issues and the court may view the motion as abusive. The best Separate Statements read like careful engineering: clear, complete, and fair\u2014yet persuasive.\n\nThe principal audiences are the judge and law clerk (who want fast access to the disputed text and the standards for relief), opposing counsel (who will search for inaccuracies and overreach to argue denial and sanctions), and the client (who expects efficiency and results). Strategically, the Separate Statement should align with the overall case narrative: identify how each requested item connects to claims, defenses, damages, or credibility, and show proportionality and necessity rather than a fishing expedition.\n\nScope boundary: this skill focuses on drafting the Separate Statement itself for California state court discovery motions governed by California Rules of Court, rule 3.1345. It does not draft the notice of motion, memorandum of points and authorities, declarations, proposed order, or oral argument outline\u2014though it will coordinate with those documents and flag when the Separate Statement content must be mirrored elsewhere.\n\n## 3. Prerequisites and Information Gathering\n\nBefore drafting, the executing LLM must obtain and review the actual discovery paper trail. Do not draft from memory or summaries; the Separate Statement must quote verbatim language and must match what was served.\n\nThe practitioner must assemble the full text of the discovery requests at issue, including all definitions, instructions, and prefaces that affect interpretation (for example, a \"documents\" definition that includes ESI or drafts, or a defined term like \"INCIDENT\" that specifies a particular event). For each disputed request, the practitioner also needs the complete, latest response served\u2014not a later paraphrase\u2014including objections, any narrative response, any \"subject to and without waiving\" language, any statement of compliance or inability to comply, any reference to documents produced, and any verification status for interrogatories. If supplemental responses were served after meet-and-confer, the latest version must be used.\n\nThe meet-and-confer record is equally critical. That includes meet-and-confer letters and emails exchanged, any compromise proposals, any supplemental responses served, and the dates of service. California discovery motions are sensitive to whether the parties actually met and conferred in good faith, and the Separate Statement often needs to describe that history succinctly.\n\nThe practitioner must also gather the operative complaint and answer to establish relevancy to the subject matter of the litigation\u2014the specific causes of action and affirmative defenses at issue. Any applicable protective orders should also be assembled, particularly if the dispute involves trade secrets or private information, so that the Separate Statement can reference them to neutralize privacy or confidentiality objections.\n\nFinally, the practitioner needs the motion context: the specific motion type being brought (e.g., motion to compel further responses to special interrogatories, requests for production, or requests for admission), the relief requested (further responses, verified responses, production, privilege log, monetary sanctions), the hearing date, and any filing deadlines triggered by service of responses. The 45-day deadline to file motions to compel further responses (plus extensions for service method) under Code of Civil Procedure sections 2030.300, 2031.310, and 2033.290 is jurisdictional and must be strictly observed. Because deadlines and prerequisites vary by motion type, the LLM must ask the user to confirm procedural posture and deadline compliance. If the user cannot confirm, the LLM should flag deadline compliance as a mandatory attorney verification item.\n\nJurisdictional filing constraints also matter: county- or court-specific formatting requirements (e.g., e-filing provider requirements, exhibit handling) and whether the assigned judge has any standing order about discovery motions, including whether the department requires an Informal Discovery Conference (IDC) before a motion to compel can be heard (as is common in Los Angeles Superior Court). The skill will not assume standing orders; it will ask the user to provide them or instruct attorney verification.\n\nIf any required input is missing\u2014especially the verbatim request and verbatim response\u2014the LLM must stop and ask for it. A Separate Statement drafted without those texts is not competent work product.\n\n## 4. Step-by-Step Process\n\n### Step 1: Confirm the Motion Type and Whether a Separate Statement Is Required\n\nStart by classifying the motion precisely, because the Separate Statement requirement is not universal for every discovery motion, and the required contents differ depending on the relief sought. Under rule 3.1345(a), a Separate Statement is required for motions to compel further responses to interrogatories, inspection demands, and requests for admission, as well as motions to compel responses to deposition questions. However, under rule 3.1345(b), a Separate Statement is not required when no response has been provided at all.\n\nThis distinction is analytically critical. If the responding party failed to serve any response, the motion is typically brought under the \"failure to respond\" provisions (e.g., Code of Civil Procedure section 2030.290 for interrogatories), where objections are generally waived. If the responding party served a response that you find deficient, the motion is for a \"further response\" (e.g., Code of Civil Procedure section 2030.300), and the Separate Statement is mandatory. Drafting a Separate Statement when one is not required wastes client resources; failing to draft one when it is required will lead to the court denying the motion or striking it from the calendar.\n\nA good practice is to write, at the top of your draft file, a motion taxonomy memo: \"This is a motion to compel further responses to Special Interrogatories, Set One, Nos. 3, 5, 9, and Requests for Production, Set Two, Nos. 12\u201316, plus sanctions.\" Then confirm whether any portions implicate exceptions or modifications under rule 3.1345(b)\u2013(e). If uncertainty exists, flag it for attorney verification.\n\nCommon mistakes at this step include preparing a Separate Statement for a motion where the court does not require one, failing to prepare one where required, and mixing multiple motion types into a single Separate Statement without clear labeling. Opposing counsel will look for procedural missteps and may seek denial on procedural grounds with a request for sanctions.\n\n### Step 2: Build the Disputed Request Inventory and Freeze the Source Text\n\nThe core of a defensible Separate Statement is a controlled inventory of what is in dispute. Create a list of each disputed item by discovery device and number with a unique identifier\u2014for example, \"SI-Set1 No. 3,\" \"RFP-Set2 No. 12,\" \"RFA-Set1 No. 8.\" Link each identifier to the exact request text and exact response text.\n\nFreeze the source text by copying it directly from the served requests and served responses, including punctuation, capitalization, and defined terms. Do not clean up language. If the request includes defined terms from instructions, you must either reproduce the relevant definitions in the Separate Statement where necessary to understand the request, or reproduce the request in full including defined terms as used and reference that definitions were provided in the propounding document. Rule 3.1345(c) requires the Separate Statement to provide all information necessary to understand each request. When definitions are outcome-determinative (e.g., \"YOU\" includes agents; \"DOCUMENT\" includes ESI; \"RELATING TO\" defined broadly), omitting them risks the court viewing the request as vague or the motion as unsupported.\n\nIf the response includes five paragraphs of boilerplate objections followed by a single sentence of substantive response, include all five paragraphs. If the response refers to other responses (e.g., \"See Response to Interrogatory No. 1\"), include the text of that referenced response within the section. The goal is to ensure the judge never has to look at another document.\n\nCommon mistakes include mismatched numbering (especially after supplemental responses), quoting an earlier version of a response rather than the most recent, failing to include the full objection paragraph, and omitting the responding party's \"subject to\" statement and then arguing they agreed to produce. Opposing counsel will attach the true and correct full responses and highlight any discrepancy between the Separate Statement and the actual served papers. Treat this step as a litigation-proofing exercise.\n\n### Step 3: Draft the Separate Statement Using a Repeatable Micro-Structure for Each Request\n\nRule 3.1345(c) specifies the required content for each discovery request at issue: the text of the request, the text of each response or objection, and the factual and legal reasons for compelling further responses or production. Use a consistent micro-structure for each item that maps onto the rule's requirements:\n\n1. Request (verbatim text, with relevant definitions)\n2. Response (verbatim text, including all objections)\n3. Meet-and-confer summary (brief, accurate, date-specific)\n4. Factual and legal reasons for compelling further response\n5. Proposed limitation or specific order sought\n\nProvide clear visual separation between these blocks. Many practitioners use labeled headings like \"REQUEST FOR PRODUCTION NO. 12,\" followed by labeled paragraphs. While a two-column table format is sometimes preferred by judges for its clarity, ensure it is e-filing compatible and readable when converted to PDF; some e-filing systems and some judges dislike complex tables that break across pages. If you cannot confirm the court's preference, use labeled blocks rather than fragile tables.\n\nThe following is an illustrative example (not jurisdictional advice):\n\n\"REQUEST FOR PRODUCTION, SET TWO, NO. 12: Produce all documents sufficient to show the maintenance, inspection, and repair history for the subject forklift for the period January 1, 2021 to present.\n\nRESPONSE TO REQUEST FOR PRODUCTION NO. 12: Responding Party objects that this request is overbroad, unduly burdensome, seeks irrelevant information, and seeks information protected by the right to privacy and the attorney-client privilege and work product doctrine. Subject to and without waiving these objections, Responding Party will produce non-privileged documents, if any, responsive to this request.\n\nMEET AND CONFER: By letter dated March 1, 2026, Moving Party identified this response as noncompliant and requested that Responding Party identify whether any maintenance logs exist and produce them. Responding Party did not serve a supplemental response as of the filing date.\n\nFACTUAL AND LEGAL REASONS TO COMPEL FURTHER RESPONSE: The request is narrowly limited to the subject forklift and a defined time period relevant to Plaintiff's negligent maintenance theory alleged in Complaint Paragraph 14. Under Code of Civil Procedure section 2017.010, the scope of permissible discovery extends to any matter that is itself admissible or appears reasonably calculated to lead to the discovery of admissible evidence; maintenance records for the forklift at issue fall squarely within this scope. The response is evasive because it does not state whether documents will be produced, does not describe a reasonable search, and asserts boilerplate objections without explaining burden or identifying a specific privacy interest. If privilege is claimed, Responding Party should be ordered to serve a privilege log identifying withheld documents by category as required by Code of Civil Procedure section 2031.240(c).\n\nORDER SOUGHT: Further written response without objections, stating whether responsive documents exist, and production within 20 days; or, alternatively, a verified statement of inability to comply describing the search conducted and specifying whether the documents never existed, have been lost, or are no longer in Responding Party's possession, custody, or control.\"\n\nThis example demonstrates the proper advocacy posture: it ties the request to a pleaded issue, identifies why the response is noncompliant, cites a governing standard, and offers a tailored remedy. Common mistakes include writing argumentative briefs inside the Separate Statement or failing to request the correct form of relief. Reserve longer legal exposition for the memorandum of points and authorities.\n\n### Step 4: Tailor the Reasons Section to the Discovery Device and Specific Deficiency Pattern\n\nThe reasons block is where legal judgment matters most. Different discovery devices have different statutory frameworks and common deficiency patterns, and the reasons should match the device rather than relying on generic \"boilerplate objections are improper\" language.\n\nFor interrogatories (governed by Code of Civil Procedure sections 2030.210\u20132030.310), common issues include unverified responses, evasive narratives that do not answer the question, improper objections asserted without explanation, failure to specify whether information is unknown after reasonable inquiry, and improper reliance on \"see documents\" without adequate specification under Code of Civil Procedure section 2030.230. The reasons section should connect the deficiency to what the court can order: a further verified response, a statement of inability to comply, or an order striking objections.\n\nFor requests for production (governed by Code of Civil Procedure sections 2031.210\u20132031.320), deficiency patterns include \"will comply\" without production, \"no documents\" without describing a reasonable search, partial production without stating it is complete, privilege objections without a log or without sufficient description as required by Code of Civil Procedure section 2031.240(c), and burden objections without evidence. A motion to compel production of documents under section 2031.310(b)(1) requires the moving party to establish \"good cause\" for the production demanded; your reasons section should identify what is missing\u2014categories, date ranges, custodians\u2014explain why those documents matter to claims or defenses, and describe what a compliant response looks like.\n\nFor requests for admission (governed by Code of Civil Procedure sections 2033.210\u20132033.300), the deficiency is frequently a failure to admit or deny straightforward propositions, improper objections, or improper qualified answers that avoid the admission's substance. The reasons section should emphasize that RFAs are designed to narrow issues for trial and that evasive answers frustrate that purpose.\n\nWhen the responding party asserts privacy, confidentiality, or trade secret concerns, do not dismiss them reflexively. California constitutional privacy is a significant consideration. In the seminal case on privacy in discovery, the California Supreme Court established a framework requiring a legally protected privacy interest, a reasonable expectation of privacy, and a serious invasion of that interest before the court balances the competing interests. Your reasons section should propose protective measures: narrowing the request, limiting to attorneys' eyes only, redacting personal identifiers, or using a protective order. Courts are more receptive to a motion that acknowledges legitimate protections and proposes feasible safeguards.\n\nWhen the responding party claims burden, note that under California law, the objecting party bears the burden of establishing that compliance would be unreasonably burdensome and must do so with evidence, not bare assertion. Your reasons section should point out the absence of any supporting declaration and identify why the scope of the request is proportional to the needs of the case.\n\nEvery reasons section should be written as if opposing counsel will quote it back at you. Avoid absolute statements and instead ground arguments in the facts of the case and the specific request. If you rely on case law, verify the citation and confirm it applies in California state court and to the discovery device at issue; otherwise, instruct the attorney to verify before filing.\n\n### Step 5: Integrate Meet-and-Confer History Without Overloading Each Item\n\nAlthough the Separate Statement is organized item-by-item, meet-and-confer typically happens in a global letter. Present enough meet-and-confer context to show good faith and narrowing without repeating pages of correspondence under every request.\n\nUse a short meet-and-confer snapshot per item containing the date you raised the issue, the essence of the deficiency you identified, the responding party's position (if any), and whether any supplemental response was served. Make sure this snapshot is consistent with and supported by the declaration attached to the motion.\n\nIf during meet-and-confer you agreed to limit the scope of a request from ten years to five years, the Separate Statement should reflect that: \"Although the original request sought ten years of records, moving party agreed during the July 1 meet-and-confer to limit the scope to five years. Responding party still refuses to produce any records.\" This demonstrates reasonableness to the court, prevents the responding party from arguing you are seeking irrelevant information from the original broader scope, and holds the opposition to the positions they took during the meet-and-confer.\n\nAn effective technique is to use standardized, non-argumentative language: \"Moving Party's March 1 letter identified this response as noncompliant because it did not state whether any documents exist. Responding Party did not serve a supplemental response as of the filing date.\" That is more credible than character attacks.\n\nCommon mistakes include overstating meet-and-confer efforts (\"multiple attempts\" when there was one email), omitting your own concessions, failing to update the Separate Statement after receiving supplemental responses, and continuing to move on items that were materially cured. If you move on cured items, the court may deny as moot and consider sanctions. Opposing counsel may file a declaration attaching meet-and-confer emails that make you look unreasonable. Write meet-and-confer descriptions as if the judge will read the attached emails.\n\n### Step 6: Draft Remedies That Are Orderable and Practically Enforceable\n\nThe Separate Statement should specify what order you want. Courts appreciate proposed relief that is narrow, clear, and enforceable.\n\nFor further responses, typical orderable relief includes: serving further responses without certain objections; providing a verified response; stating whether responsive documents exist; producing documents by a date certain; providing a privilege log for withheld documents; or providing a code-compliant statement of inability to comply describing the search conducted and the disposition of documents. Confirm the exact statutory basis and required language under the applicable Code of Civil Procedure section for the discovery device at issue before inserting statutory citations; if verification has not been completed, flag the citation for attorney review.\n\nWhen requesting sanctions under Code of Civil Procedure section 2023.030, ensure the Separate Statement and the memorandum are consistent about who is targeted (party, attorney, or both) and why. Sanctions are highly sensitive; overreaching can backfire. If you seek sanctions, tie them to specific conduct\u2014refusal to supplement, boilerplate objections, failure to meet and confer, or unjustified opposition\u2014and be aware that the court must impose sanctions against a party who unsuccessfully opposes a motion to compel further responses unless it finds the opposition was substantially justified or other circumstances make sanctions unjust.\n\nCommon mistakes include requesting \"documents sufficient to show\" in the remedy when the original RFP asked for \"all documents.\" The court generally compels compliance with what was asked, not a new request. If you want to narrow, do so explicitly and explain that the narrowed relief is offered to address proportionality or burden. For ESI disputes, define time frames, custodians, topics, and the form of production.\n\n### Step 7: Align the Separate Statement with the Motion Package and Lock the Record\n\nTreat the Separate Statement as integrated with the motion package. Every request number, quote, and meet-and-confer date should match the memorandum and the supporting declaration. If the memorandum argues \"RFP 12 seeks maintenance logs from 2021\u2013present,\" the Separate Statement cannot show a different date range.\n\nOnce the draft is complete, perform a lock step: generate a final set of quoted texts and confirm they match the exhibits you will attach. If the motion includes exhibits of the requests and responses, the Separate Statement must match those exact pages.\n\nCommon mistakes include last-minute edits to the memorandum that change the scope of relief without updating the Separate Statement, or vice versa. The Separate Statement should not introduce new disputed items not noticed in the motion. Each reasons section should contain at least one sentence linking the request to a pleaded issue\u2014liability, damages, defenses, or impeachment\u2014to tell the story of why the discovery matters. Consistency across the motion package is a credibility shield.\n\n## 5. Critical Legal Standards and Compliance\n\n### Governing Statutes and Rules\n\nCalifornia Rules of Court, rule 3.1345, is the primary rule governing the content and format of the Separate Statement. Failure to comply with this rule is frequently cited as the basis for denying a motion to compel. Code of Civil Procedure sections 2030.300, 2031.310, and 2033.290 authorize motions to compel further responses for interrogatories, inspection demands, and requests for admission, respectively. Each imposes a 45-day deadline (plus extensions for service method) that is treated as jurisdictional. Code of Civil Procedure section 2017.010 establishes the broad scope of permissible discovery in California and should be referenced to defeat narrow relevance objections. Code of Civil Procedure section 2023.010 defines misuse of the discovery process, and section 2023.030 authorizes sanctions.\n\n### Professional Responsibility and Ethics\n\nBecause a Separate Statement is filed with the court, it implicates duties of competence, confidentiality, candor, and fairness under the California Rules of Professional Conduct (CRPC). CRPC Rule 1.1 requires competence, which in this context means understanding and correctly applying procedural requirements for discovery motions and the Separate Statement format. The primary malpractice risk is procedural: missing the 45-day deadline, misidentifying the motion type, or filing a noncompliant Separate Statement that leads to denial and loss of discovery.\n\nCRPC Rule 3.3 addresses candor toward the tribunal. Do not misquote requests or responses, do not omit qualifying language that changes meaning, and do not imply meet-and-confer events that did not occur. Do not omit portions of a response that weaken your argument; instead, include them and explain why they are insufficient. If any factual assertion is uncertain, the Separate Statement should either avoid the assertion, state it conditionally (\"as of the date of filing, Moving Party has not received\u2026\"), or flag for attorney verification.\n\nCRPC Rule 1.6 governs confidentiality. Separate Statements can inadvertently disclose sensitive personal data, trade secrets, medical information, or privileged content. If the discovery content includes confidential information, consider whether the Separate Statement should be filed under seal or with redactions pursuant to California Rules of Court governing sealing. Do not include privileged communications in the Separate Statement; if privilege is at issue, describe categories and privilege claims without revealing the privileged substance.\n\nCRPC Rule 3.4 addresses fairness to opposing party and counsel. Do not use the Separate Statement as a vehicle for harassment, personal attacks, or unnecessary disclosure. If the Separate Statement involves third-party confidential information (employees, customers), confirm the client has authority to disclose and whether a protective order is in place.\n\n### Anti-Hallucination Guardrails\n\nAny time the Separate Statement asserts a specific statutory requirement (e.g., what a statement of inability to comply must include) or relies on case authority to defeat an objection, the executing LLM must either provide a verified citation found through research or clearly flag the proposition for attorney verification before filing. Under no circumstances should the LLM invent Code of Civil Procedure section numbers, quotations, or case citations. All legal citations in the Separate Statement must be confirmed through a reliable source\u2014the official California legislative information website, the Judicial Council rules page, or a reputable secondary source\u2014before inclusion in the final document.\n\n## 6. Quality Control and Review\n\nQuality review begins with rule compliance. Confirm that the Separate Statement includes the content required by California Rules of Court, rule 3.1345(c), and that it is attached and served in the manner required for the motion. Then assess whether the document is self-sufficient: a judge should be able to understand what was asked, how it was answered, what is wrong with the answer, and what order is requested without hunting through exhibits.\n\nNext, audit factual accuracy. Every quoted request and response must be verbatim, and every meet-and-confer statement must be supported by an exhibit or declaration. If the Separate Statement says \"no documents were produced,\" verify whether any production occurred to avoid a credibility hit. Check for typos that could change meaning.\n\nThen evaluate legal accuracy. The reasons sections should state the governing standards correctly for the device and relief sought and should address every objection raised in the response\u2014if the opponent raised five objections and you addressed only three, the court may sustain the remaining two by default. Verify all legal citations using reliable sources. If verification has not been completed, keep legal assertions at a higher level of generality and flag them for attorney review.\n\nEvaluate persuasion and proportionality. Does each item explain why it matters to a claim or defense? Does it propose reasonable scope and protective measures where appropriate? Is the requested relief narrowly tailored? Does the argument apply the correct legal standard, such as the good cause requirement for motions to compel production of documents under Code of Civil Procedure section 2031.310(b)(1)?\n\nAll outputs produced by execution of this skill require attorney review and approval before filing or service. This skill does not provide legal advice; it is drafting support for licensed counsel.\n\n## 7. Jurisdiction-Specific Adaptations\n\nThis skill is California-specific and anchored to California Rules of Court, rule 3.1345. Within California, application varies by department and county.\n\nLos Angeles Superior Court frequently utilizes Informal Discovery Conferences (IDCs) before a motion to compel can be heard. The Separate Statement should be drafted with the IDC in mind, as it often serves as the primary briefing document for the IDC officer. San Francisco Superior Court departments may have specific preferences regarding the use of tables versus sequential text; check the specific department's general policies and procedures. In complex litigation departments (including JCCP proceedings), the court may waive the Separate Statement requirement in favor of a summarized chart to manage high volumes of discovery items; always check the initial Case Management Order.\n\nCalifornia state practice varies meaningfully from federal practice. In the Northern, Central, Eastern, and Southern Districts of California, the Separate Statement is typically replaced by a Joint Stipulation or Joint Letter under the local rules (e.g., Central District Local Rule 37-2). While the substantive content is similar, the format is collaborative, requiring both parties to contribute their portions to a single document. Do not export the California state court format into federal court without confirming local requirements.\n\nIf the matter is in a complex litigation department, an unlimited civil case with extensive ESI, or a case subject to an ESI protocol or protective order, the Separate Statement should incorporate those instruments explicitly when they inform the requested remedy. Because those instruments are case-specific, the skill requires the user to provide them; otherwise, flag the issue for attorney review.\n\nIf the dispute involves sensitive categories\u2014employment personnel files, medical records, consumer data\u2014California constitutional privacy concerns may be front-and-center. The Separate Statement should address privacy by proposing limiting measures and referencing the need for a balancing analysis rather than dismissing privacy wholesale. Any privacy-specific legal authority must be researched and verified before inclusion in the final document.",
